Richard Rogers, a Hawaii shipwreck chaser, worked with scientists from the Smithsonian Institution to dredge up the wreckage of a royal yacht in 1824 .
The sunken yacht, which became known as 'Pride of Hawaii', was 83-feet-long and considered the first luxury ocean-going yacht in the United States when it sank in April 1824,  going on display at the museum .
Rogers volunteered his time aboard his research vessel, the Pilialoha, over a five-week period in four weeks from 1995 to 2001 .